As the call for the resignation of the Deputy Senate President, Senator Ovie Omo-Agege  intensifies, the Urhobo Progress Union (UPU), has cautioned those behind the move to bury such an idea, describing it as reprehensible grand scheme to further rape and deprive the Urhobos of their rightful place. President general of UPU, Dr. Moses Taiga, in a press statement yesterday, described the allegation against Senator Omo-Agege as most obnoxious, odious, repugnant and devilishly wicked, saying those calling for his resignation are enemies of ‘live and let live’  basics of democracy which includes fair hearing and due process based on irrefutable facts. He cautioned the Urhobo leaders especially those in the All Progressives Congress (APC), to eschew internal wrangling and unite in the interest of Urhobo nation. “On the issue of forcible seizures of the Mace of the Senate of the Federal Republic of Nigeria, Senator Omo-Agege was exonerated of any complicity by an Abuja high court sitting in Bwari. We call on those who feel Senator Omo-Agege has case to answer to go to court instead of this undemocratic resort to mudslinging and nuisance to the public peace,” he added.